.Dd March 27, 2026
.Dt SORT 1
.Os Kayako
.Sh NAME
.Nm sort
.Nd sort, merge, or sequence check text files
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.Nm
.Op Fl cmu
.Op Fl o Ar output
.Op Fl nr
.Op Ar file ...
.Sh DESCRIPTION
The
.Nm
utility conforms to POSIX.1-2024. It reads lines from the specified
.Ar file
operands and writes them to the standard output.
.Pp
If no
.Ar file
operands are specified, or if a
.Ar file
operand is
.Pq Ql - ,
the standard input is read.
.Pp
The following options are supported:
.Bl -tag -width indent
.It Fl c
Check that the single input file is ordered. If the file is out of sequence,
.Nm
writes no output and exits with a non-zero status.
.It Fl m
Merge only; the input files are assumed to be already sorted.
.It Fl n
Restrict the sort key to an initial numeric string.
.It Fl o Ar output
Specify the name of an
.Ar output
file to be used instead of the standard output. This file can be the same
as one of the input
.Ar files .
.It Fl r
Reverse the sense of comparisons.
.It Fl u
Unique: suppress all but one in each set of lines having equal keys.
If used with
.Fl c ,
verify that the input contains no adjacent duplicate lines.
.El
.Sh EXIT STATUS
The following exit values are returned:
.Bl -tag -width indent
.It 0
All input files were output successfully, or
.Fl c
was specified and the input file was correctly sorted.
.It 1
Under the
.Fl c
option, the file was not ordered as specified, or if
.Fl c
and
.Fl u
were specified, two adjacent lines were identical.
.It >1
An error occurred.
.El
.Sh EXAMPLES
Sort a list of numbers in reverse order:
.Pp
.Dl $ sort -nr numbers.txt
.Pp
Check if a file is already sorted:
.Pp
.Dl $ sort -c names.txt || echo "File is unsorted"
.Pp
Merge two sorted files into a third:
.Pp
.Dl $ sort -m -o total.txt file1.txt file2.txt
.Sh SEE ALSO
.Xr comm 1 ,
.Xr join 1 ,
.Xr uniq 1
